<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 30 日，星期日 22:04:42 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Show That Knows the Secret to Serialized TV]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Yair Rosenberg 的娱乐必备<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1IJm7MhDj5qxKLJ7SjLICWbQ9bA=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/babylon_5/original.jpg" alt="巴比伦5号空间站图片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>华纳兄弟。</figcaption></figure><small><i data-stringify-type="italic">这是</i>《大西洋<i data-stringify-type="italic">日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br>欢迎回到《每日邮报》的周日文化版，一位<i>大西洋月刊的</i>作家在其中揭示了是什么让他们开心。<br><br>今天的特邀嘉宾是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>特约撰稿人亚伊尔·罗森伯格。 Yair 撰写有关政治、文化和宗教交集的文章，也是我们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/">Deep Shtetl</a>时事通讯的作者。他最近揭示了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-supreme-court-netanyahu-parliament/674833/">以色列社会信任崩溃的情况</a>，提供了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">建立更好的社交媒体平台</a>的路线图， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6494bbb2a1d6420038c5cb21/congress-antisemitism-yair-rosenberg/">在国会就反犹太主义作证</a>，并与演员本普拉特谈论了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/641c6dfed18ff80037f5eb02/ben-platt-parade-interview-yair-rosenberg-jews/">犹太教在表演者作品中所扮演的角色。百老汇</a>。亚尔目前正在创作一本独特的科幻短篇小说集，尽管给洋基队带来了巨大的痛苦，但仍为洋基队加油，并回忆了一项已不复存在的神奇科技。<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三篇周日读物：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/sound-of-freedom-qanon-culture-war/674832/">“我看了‘他们’不想让你看的电影。”</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/">芭比就是一切。肯就是其他一切。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/">这首歌曲首次俘获了西妮德·奥康纳的力量</a></li><b>文化调查：Yair Rosenberg</b><br><br><b>我十几岁时就喜欢的一种文化产品：</b>在高中时，我最珍贵的财产之一是便携式 DVD 播放器。这正是它听起来的样子：带有屏幕的翻盖设备，可以播放光盘上的电影。拥有一台意味着我可以在学校越野旅行时观看<i>《指环王》</i> ，或者躲在自己的房间里狂看 Netflix 的电视节目（那时他们还给你寄 DVD）。我费了好大劲才说服父母帮我拿到那东西，以前我去哪儿都带着它。如今，便携式播放器已成为博物馆藏品，早已被功能更强大、播放更高质量视频的智能手机所取代。但再多的处理能力或像素分辨率也无法取代公交车上那个可以点播电影的怪孩子的魔力。<br><br><b>我最近重新观看、重读或以其他方式重温的东西：</b>我最喜欢的电视节目之一是一部古怪的 90 年代科幻传奇，名为<i>《巴比伦 5》</i> 。该剧的独特之处在于其创作者 J. Michael Straczynski 提前规划了整个五年的故事情节。他基本上写了整部小说，然后将其搬上银幕。正如我为<i>《大西洋月刊》</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/harry-potter-hbo-reboot-tv-series-jk-rowling/673816/">所写的</a>那样，当今大多数连续剧电视节目都令我失望。他们的情节往往不会成功，因为编剧们都是边编边编。 <i>《迷失》</i>就是一个典型的例子，但还有很多其他例子。 <i>《巴比伦5》</i>则相反，它不断地预示事件——有时甚至提前整季——并带领角色踏上可信的成长、发现和悲剧之旅。我一直在重温这部剧，因为它很令人愉快，而且还因为斯特拉钦斯基将于下个月以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt27712788/">原创动画电影</a>的形式发布这个故事的新部分。<br><br><b>我最喜欢的大片和最喜欢的艺术电影：</b>我是那些不仅在前面提到的便携式 DVD 播放器上观看每部<i>《指环王》</i>电影的加长版，而且还与所有演员和工作人员一起观看多次的人之一评论。这就是我知道重要事情的方式，比如当布景设计师试图为角色在被洪水淹没的艾辛格堡垒中创造一条漂浮的苹果路径时，制作是如何暂时中断的，结果苹果拒绝漂浮。最终，他们意识到自己被设计完美的蜡制道具水果愚弄了。<br><br>我在聚会上很受欢迎。<br><br>至于艺术电影，这可能是一种作弊，但我会选择<i>脚注</i>。这是一部外语电影，所以从定义上来说并不是一部大片，但它确实赢得了以色列相当于奥斯卡奖的最佳影片奖，并且在 2012 年获得了真正的奥斯卡最佳外语片奖。正如我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6351cf31fb1fdd00362a68d8/guide-jewish-history-culture-anti-semitism/">在其他地方</a>所说的那样，“它是可以肯定地说，导演约瑟夫·锡达的<i>《脚注》</i>是您看过的唯一一部获得奥斯卡提名的关于塔木德学者的戏剧喜剧。这也是一部关于父子、代际冲突以及古往今来犹太文本激发的激情的非凡电影。”这部电影取材于现实生活中的一个学术王朝，其成员包括我自己的亲戚，这并没有什么坏处。 <b>[相关：</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6351cf31fb1fdd00362a68d8/guide-jewish-history-culture-anti-semitism/">如何从犹太人而不是讨厌他们的人那里了解犹太人</a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我什么都会看的演员：</b>彼得·萨斯加德。他拥有令人难以置信的魅力和范围，无论是在《<i>破碎的玻璃》</i> （有史以来关于现代新闻业的最佳电影）中扮演一位顽强的杂志编辑，揭露他的一位明星记者的寓言，还是在<i>《教育》</i>中体现一个掠夺性但具有磁性的骗子艺术家，<i> </i>诱捕一位易受影响的大学生（由伟大的凯瑞·穆里根扮演）和她的家人。<br><br><b>我最近读过的最好的小说作品：</b>我一直在努力阅读一本新的科幻短篇小说选集，名为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/jewish-futures-science-fiction-from-the-world-s-oldest-diaspora-michael-a-burstein/9781515458050?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《犹太未来》</i></a> 。它将于下个月发布，但我在 Kickstarter 上支持了该项目，所以我得到了一份预发本。我迫不及待地想让其他人能够阅读它——不仅仅是因为我姐姐对此做出了贡献。与所有选集一样，不同的故事会向不同的读者讲述，但迄今为止我最喜欢的是 Leah Cypess 的搞笑《Frummer House》，讲述了当智能家居开始对其居民强加宗教仪式时会发生什么； 《The Ascent》是亚伯拉罕·约瑟芬·里斯曼 (Abraham Josephine Riesman) 和 SI·罗森鲍姆 (SI Rosenbaum) 创作的关于耶路撒冷永恒修复和毁灭的令人难忘的故事；当然，还有我姐姐 SM Rosenberg 的《月亮旋律》，它是米德拉什和超级英雄故事的结合体。<br><br><b>最后一个让我哭泣的文化或娱乐事件：</b>纽约洋基队的进攻，或者更确切地说，缺乏进攻。<br><br><b>我最近收到的一个很好的文化或娱乐建议：</b>停止观看洋基队。我没有听。<br><br><b>一位对我来说意义重大的音乐艺术家：</b>我喜欢爱尔兰民间音乐——它的合唱品质、它的代际吸引力、它反映和延续文化记忆的方式。我会听当代四重奏组 The High Kings 录制的任何歌曲。该乐队的所有四名成员都是多乐器演奏家，拥有令人难以置信的独特声音，以某种方式无缝地融入四声部和声。他们自 2008 年以来一直在创作音乐，他们的专长是通过忠实于原始精髓的现代编曲，将经典的爱尔兰吉格舞和民谣带给新的听众。当我不写作时，我的副业爱好是作曲、唱歌和录制犹太音乐，我的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://bit.ly/azyashir">第一张专辑</a>深受这种方法的影响，将传统的安息日歌曲与现代旋律和乐器结合起来。<br><br><b>我会读任何作品的作家：</b>石黑一雄，既因为他的写作毫不费力地优雅，也因为它奖励对道德主题的更深入思考。举个例子：我最近读了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-buried-giant-kazuo-ishiguro/9780307455796?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《被掩埋的巨人》</i></a> ，它让我进入了另一本书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/forgiveness-an-alternative-account-matthew-ichihashi-potts/9780300259858?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>宽恕》</i></a> ，作者是哈佛大学纪念教堂的首席牧师马修·市桥·波茨（Matthew Ichihashi Potts），他使用了几部文学作品（包括石黑一雄的作品）来挑战传统观念宽恕并提供替代方法。 <b>[相关</b>： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/63399d48fb1fdd0036293c1e/yom-kippur-forgiveness-anti-semitism-antepli/">我最喜欢的反犹太主义者教给我关于宽恕的知识</a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我上一次关于文化的辩论：</b>今年早些时候，我在佛罗里达州的近 1000 人面前就政治和文化中的反犹太主义问题与保守派评论员本·夏皮罗 (Ben Shapiro)<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gh6CYPboQjg">进行了辩论</a>。我们解决了从 Ye 到 Joe Rogan 的所有问题，并且几乎创造了每分钟说出最多单词的世界纪录。 （我成为一名记者的原因之一是人们可以按照自己的速度阅读我的内容，而这在现场听我讲话时是不可能的。）<br><br><b>我回到一首诗或诗行：</b> “把你的面包撒在水面上，因为多日之后，你就会找到它”（传道书 11:1）。有时，写看似无情的社会力量和不公正现象可能会让人感到徒劳。但我发现你永远不知道你的话语会在哪里被听到，以及它们最终会产生什么影响。<br><br><strong>未来一周</strong><br><br><li>安·帕切特 (Ann Patchett) 的新小说《汤姆·莱克》( <a href="https://tertulia.com/book/tom-lake-ann-patchett/9780063327528?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Tom Lake</i></a> ) 探讨了父母在孩子出生前的浪漫史（周二发售）。</li><li>斯特林·哈乔 (Sterlin Harjo) 和塔伊卡·维迪蒂 (Taika Waititi) 创作的喜剧系列<a href="https://www.fxnetworks.com/shows/reservation-dogs"><i>《保留地狗》</i></a>第三季也是最后一季将于周三首播（在 Hulu 上播出）。</li><li>由成龙和塞斯·罗根配音的<a href="https://www.teenagemutantninjaturtlesmovie.com/?gclid=CjwKCAjwzo2mBhAUEiwAf7wjkq5qsml1R5NNWLU67VThcivgiM04HN5SbJI3XqiO_gJTBrbqlNhRyRoCJ0MQAvD_BwE"><i>《忍者神龟：突变混乱》</i></a> （周三上映）<i> </i></li><strong>散文</strong><br><br>美国家庭生活不应该如此动荡<br><br><em>艾略特·哈斯佩尔</em><br><br><p>为人父母总是充满不可预测性：凌晨两点醒来，学校打来电话，那些让<i>我胃痛的</i>可怕话语。这种日常差异通常源于生病或受惊的孩子，并且是家庭生活基本动态的一部分。然而，今天的美国父母也面临着日益严重的外部干扰和旨在提供稳定的机构的退化。其结果是，许多家庭经常会因为一些问题而陷入困境，这些问题不仅仅是不方便，但还不是灾难性的。这会滋生父母的压力、不安全感和疲惫。简而言之，美国人已经进入了一个颤抖的时代。</p><p>过去半个世纪以来，这个国家一直在走这条道路。从 20 世纪 70 年代开始，一系列经济和社会政策决策导致了政治学家雅各布·哈克 (Jacob Hacker) 所说的从政府和企业到家庭的<a href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-risk-shift-the-new-economic-insecurity-and-the-decline-of-the-american-dream-jacob-s-hacker/9780190844141?affiliate_id=atl-347">“巨大风险转移”</a> 。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><strong>更多文化内容</strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-richard-rhodes-interview/674828/">奥本海默专家观察<i>奥本海默</i>。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">格蕾塔·葛韦格在《芭比乐园》中的课程</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/new-york-picking-up-dog-poop/674825/">什么样的恶棍不清理他们的狗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/lifelong-learning-new-skill-book-recommendations/674807/">终身学习者的七本书</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/the-jewish-catalog-50th-anniversary/674846/">当犹太教走向点菜时</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbenheimer-movie-theaters-hollywood-strikes/674822/">好莱坞的<i>巴本海默</i>失手</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/evolution-liars-of-nature-lixing-sun-review/674808/">大自然会说谎吗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/a-poem-by-janelle-tan-claude-glass-as-night-song/674800/">诗：《克劳德·格拉斯作为夜歌》</a></li><strong>赶上<em>大西洋</em></strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/chronic-fatigue-long-covid-symptoms/674834/">疲劳会击垮一个人。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/07/are-you-plagued-by-the-feeling-that-everyone-used-to-be-nicer/674838/">你是否因为每个人都曾经变得更好的感觉而困扰？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-defies-voting-rights-act-supreme-court/674850/">阿拉巴马州在投票权问题上藐视最高法院。</a></li><strong>相片集</strong><br><br>澳大利亚女足世界杯、巴黎 Lollapalooza 艺术节的表演，以及编辑精选的本周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-of-the-week-feathered-gorilla-breaching-whale-alphorn-festival/674853/">最佳照片</a>中的更多内容<br><br><i data-stringify-type="italic">Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">探索我们所有的时事通讯。</a></em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/babylon-5-serialized-tv-show-recommendations/674861/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/babylon-5-serialized-tv-show-recommendations/674861/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[I Wish I Could Remember]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一首献给周日的诗<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/EwVdlaEqIt68ns4fDxL-sLYm0Wk=/0x0:3000x1688/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/sunday_poem/original.jpg" alt="一张女人的手放在男人手上的黑白照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>南希·博罗威克</figcaption></figure>你说的话让我们大笑<br>直到我们倒回床上<br>并叹了口气。事实是，我们从来没有<br><br>比那时的我们更加相爱<br>当所有的化疗、放疗、<br>一切都结束了。我们<br><br>牵着手。有时候，我会倾身过去<br>重新调整您的插管<br>帮助您呼吸。有时候，我会梦见<br><br>我们顺流而下，<br>我们都没有注意到<br>我们漂流而下的河流<br><br>已经变得太宽了，看不到海岸<br>两侧。<em>这只是一个梦</em>，<br>我会告诉自己。但梦想是怎样的<br><br>我们穿越黑暗，为什么<br>我听到氧气的嘶嘶声——<br>海浪拍打着我们的船头——<br><br>今天早上当我的思绪转向你时<br>试图记住，十年<br>十年后，你说的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/poem-michael-white-i-wish-i-could-remember/674867/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/poem-michael-white-i-wish-i-could-remember/674867/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Weird, Fragmented World of Social Media After Twitter]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>埃隆·马斯克摧毁的公共论坛永远不会被取代——没关系。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hQLqXeptJBp-yYoePJjV8bbbp_k=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/after_twitter/original.jpg" alt="一只蓝色的鸟在飞离巢穴时掉落羽毛" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂图片社。</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">你在蓝天吗</span>？老实说：可能不是。 Twitter 的克隆版仍处于测试阶段，并且其邀请码一直是出了名的吝啬。它的规模较小，这意味着每次新用户涌入时，现有用户群都会感到恐慌，算法策划的“发现”选项卡中充满了令人难以置信的过度抱怨。最近一篇引起广泛讨论的帖子感叹，“蓝天长者”——在这里我应该指出，这是一项在二月份才推出移动版本的服务——因为所有的攻击而遭受着降级的体验。这句话已经成为一个即时模因。<br><br>关于 Bluesky，您只需要了解两件事。首先，它的用户正试图让<em>“skeeting”</em>一词成为现实，尽管它是比 Mastodon 的<em>“tooting”</em>更糟糕的<em>推文</em>替代方案。第二是它始终处于高度情绪化状态。现在，滚动 Twitter 的“为你”选项卡就像在装满业余种族科学家和罗马雕像化身的碗里捞苹果，哀叹我们不再建造大教堂，而 Bluesky 的类似内容则讨论了向网站开发者发送死亡威胁是否合理。如果他们确实值得的话，这是可以接受的。<br><br>据我所知，Bluesky 正在吸走 Twitter 上情绪最失调的用户和最忠实的垃圾发布者。我不敢在那里发帖——根据追踪服务，我的账户曾一度是该应用程序上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wolfgang.raios.xyz/top_blocked">被封锁最多的</a>账户——但很高兴看到一个小而紧密、政治上独特的社区已经形成，尽管围绕着包括仇恨在内的共同利益我。虽然 Bluesky 的规模只是大型社交网络的一小部分，但它似乎已经达到了维持自身所需的临界质量，这表明埃隆·马斯克在 Twitter 上的行为已经无可挽回地破坏了该服务。无论从字面上还是隐喻上来说，我们现在都生活在后推特时代。马斯克重塑品牌后， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/"><em>X</em></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">标志着很多人不再愿意去的地方</a>。<br><br>直到最近，我还怀疑即使是像马斯克这样草率、反复无常的老板也能打垮 Twitter。留在那里的自恋者和瘾君子会让藤壶相形见绌。该网站一直比 Facebook 小得多，它之所以重要只是因为政客、记者和目前被认为是公共知识分子的人都在使用它。无论您阅读<em>《</em><em>纽约时报》</em>还是观看福克斯新闻，您都会遇到源自 Twitter 的内容。当推特将唐纳德·特朗普踢出局时，这严重削弱了他破坏新闻议程的能力，因为记者根本不准备加入这位前总统本人控制的右翼平台“真相社会”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">摘自2022年5月号：为什么过去10年美国人的生活特别愚蠢</a><br><br>不过现在，我可以看到后 Twitter 世界的第一缕曙光。怪人、早期采用者、垃圾海报、毛茸茸的人和责骂者正在尝试 Bluesky，在那里他们可以抱怨“Elmo”和他负责“鸟类网站”的任期。真正的年轻人都在使用 TikTok。真正的婴儿潮一代从未在 Twitter 上出现过，但仍然很高兴<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-midlife-crisis-boomerbook/620307/">在 Facebook 上发布</a>有关 UFO 和 Bunco 之夜的内容。一些心怀不满的推特用户尝试了 Post 和 Mastodon，但第一个是墓地，第二个是非技术用户的障碍训练场。普通人和品牌转向 Instagram 的新 Threads 应用程序，然后许多普通人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://uk.pcmag.com/social-media/147939/yikes-threads-user-traffic-falls-74-from-initial-high">立即离开</a>，因为 Threads 太无聊了，没有足够的怪人、毛茸茸的人或责骂来添加调味品。 （企业可能喜欢将广告放在无可争议的励志内容旁边，但累积的效果是让 Threads 就像观看完全由电视广告组成的电视频道一样。） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9rVcCR5IQE">Grindfluencers</a> - 听 15 分钟<em>《魔鬼经济学</em>》和<em>《艺术》</em>摘要的人<em>of War——</em>一直在 LinkedIn 上最开心，发布他们的播客内容并祝贺你的“工作周年纪念日”，这不是也永远不会是真实的事情。 Instagram 上仍然充满了感到#blessed 的性感人士，并热衷于穿着比基尼在无边泳池边摆​​姿势来展示这种谦逊。 （如果这些海报上有一个性感的妹妹，她也可以穿比基尼，然后他们就可以观察到#familyiseverything。） Twitter 现在是那些知道<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://unherd.com/thepost/did-the-desantis-campaign-know-it-was-using-a-nazi-symbol/">Sonnenrad</a>是什么并且相信它已经成为人们的首选社交网络。受到不公正的诽谤。<br><br>有些人会在考虑了上述所有选项后，最终决定接触草地。<br><br>社交媒体早期<span class="smallcaps">的许多争议都</span>源于这样的假设：用户在跨平台上拥有单一、一致的身份。研究人员达纳·博伊德和爱丽丝·马威克将由此产生的不和谐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/31/web-concepts-need-understand-2015-guide-netiquette">描述</a>为“语境崩溃”：用户在 Twitter 或 Facebook 上潜在的无限受众面前，像在私人房间里一样随意发言，招致批评。很多时候，两个亲密朋友之间本可以致命的笑话在<em>BuzzFeed</em>列表文章或电视新闻 chyron 中却遭到更广泛的反对。现在我们已经更擅长在不同的空间将自己分类为不同的模式，以至于我看到人们感叹他们在 Instagram 上知道自己是谁，在 Twitter 上知道自己是谁，<em>但我不知道自己是谁在线程上</em>。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">Yair Rosenberg：如何挽救社交媒体</a><br><br>考虑到这一趋势，令人惊讶的不是 Twitter 现在已经分裂，而是它持续了这么久。多年来，这里一直是角斗士和狮子自愿加入的竞技场。 Twitter 允许对库进行恶意攻击，也允许库针对规模稍小的库发起取消活动。<br><br>那健康吗？很长一段时间，我都担心 Upworthy 联合创始人 Eli Pariser 所说的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ted.com/talks/eli_pariser_beware_online_filter_bubbles?language=en">过滤气泡</a>”的扩散，他将其定义为“你生活在网上的个人的、独特的信息宇宙”。我想，也许两极分化是由于我们被囚禁在回音室中而导致的，而我们正在屈服于多元化的无知——缺乏对多数观点的认识。现在我想知道过去十年的社交媒体是否让我们在另一个方向上走得太远，花太多时间与与我们不同的人在一起，以夸大我们差异的方式聚集在一起。<br><br> 2018 年，理性主义博主斯科特·亚历山大 (Scott Alexander) 发表了一篇名为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slatestarcodex.com/2018/10/30/sort-by-controversial/">按争议排序</a>”的短篇小说。其中，一名科技初创公司的员工发明了一个程序，可以输出“剪刀声明”——立即将群体分成两半的断言。世界避免陷入无休无止的低级战争，只是因为她不小心创造了一份剪刀声明，在公司工作完成之前将公司撕裂。这个故事抓住了社交媒体作为对阳光下每个主题进行滚动公投的感觉。您是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/columnist/2023/05/26/can-i-recline-my-seat-on-a-plane/70253628007/">飞机座椅</a>躺椅吗？如果来访的孩子在您家呆到很晚，您必须为他们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2022/06/04/1103075936/-swedengate-alleges-the-swedes-dont-feed-other-peoples-children-on-playdates">提供</a>晚餐吗？ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.buzzfeed.com/catesish/help-am-i-going-insane-its-definitely-blue">这件衣服</a>是蓝色的还是白色的？在政治辩论中，这意味着被迫灌输政治对手最令人头疼的痴迷。以 Twitter 账户 Libs of TikTok 为例，该账户的存在纯粹是为了从一个社交网络收集超前卫的观点，并将其提供给另一个社交网络作为愤怒的诱饵。它的流行让我认为过滤气泡，至少以温和的形式，可能不是一个坏主意。<br><br>为了蓬勃发展，社区需要界限和规范，甚至，上帝保佑我们，长辈。这就是为什么我喜欢把鼻子伸进 Bluesky 并时常深吸一口气。对于那些对动漫生殖器和有关米奇·麦康奈尔的残酷笑话都感兴趣的人们来说，这是一个有围墙的花园。他们在那里很开心。你可能不会。没关系。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-alternatives-bluesky-mastodon-threads/674859/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-alternatives-bluesky-mastodon-threads/674859/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[One More COVID Summer?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>年中浪潮可能正在连续第四年酝酿。会一直这样吗？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ho_TtxSm1W41SD_VW5hNZB-_8Eo=/1x0:965x542/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/SummerCovid2/original.gif" alt="冠状病毒粒子的动画，太阳和云在其内部移动" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/大西洋月刊；资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>自疫情爆发初期以来，流行病学家就一直在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/11/covid-seasonal-winter/620766/">等待</a>冠状病毒最终摆脱泛季节狂潮。不会再有像 2020 年第一波袭击美国那样的春季浪潮，也不会再有像当年掀起热疫苗夏季浪潮的年中浪潮。最终，或者说希望落空了，SARS-CoV-2将遵循许多其他呼吸道病原体所遵循的相同日历，至少在全球温带地区：一个严酷的冬季高峰，然后是一个休假的夏季。<br><br>但疫情爆发已经三年半了，冠状病毒仍然顽固地拒绝让最温暖的月份休息一下。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://yourlocalepidemiologist.substack.com/p/covid-19-catch-up-quick">一些</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://caitlinrivers.substack.com/p/this-week-in-outbreaks-july-28-edition">公共卫生专家</a>现在担心，在经历了一段相对平静的时期后，该病毒正在掀起另一波夏季浪潮。在美国南部和东北部，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://biobot.io/data/">废水</a>中冠状病毒的浓度几周来一直在缓慢上升，中西部和西部地区也紧随其后；检测阳性率、急诊室诊断出的 COVID-19 以及<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#maps_new-admissions-rate-county">住院人数</a>也在上升。绝对数字仍然很小，而且可能会保持这种状态。但约翰霍普金斯大学的流行病学家凯特琳·里弗斯表示，这些都是年中浪潮正在酝酿的明显早期迹象，这将使今年夏天连续第四个夏天出现明显的冠状病毒爆发。<br><br>然而，即使疫情已经蔓延到如此程度，仍然没有人能确定夏季浪潮是否是新冠病毒的永久常态，或者该病毒是否表现出可预测的季节性模式。没有任何自然法则规定冬天一定会出现呼吸道疾病，或者夏天则不会。 “我们只是不太了解是什么驱动了呼吸道感染的周期性模式，”东北大学传染病建模师萨姆·斯卡皮诺（Sam Scarpino）说。这意味着今年任何时候这种病毒都无法保证让我们有任何懈怠。<br><br>许多病原体<em>会</em>随着季节的变化而盛衰，这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.plos.org/plospathogens/article?id=10.1371/journal.ppat.1007327">无可争议的</a>。在世界温带地区，空气中的虫子在冬天会大量繁殖，但在炎热的天气里就会被抑制。与此同时，脊髓灰质炎和其他粪便传播的病原体以及淋病和其他一些性传播感染通常在夏季上升。但注意到这些趋势是一回事，另一回事是另一回事。真正理解触发因素是另一回事。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/11/covid-seasonal-winter/620766/">阅读：新冠病毒现在看起来确实是季节性的</a><br><br>有些疾病更容易解释：在赤道附近，寨卡病毒和基孔肯雅热等<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5963813/">蚊媒疾病</a>的浪潮往往与携带它们的昆虫依赖天气的生命周期有关；在世界温带地区，莱姆病的发病率与夏季蜱虫的活动有关。流感也有相当有力的数据支持其对冬季的偏好。这种病毒包裹在一层称为包膜的脆弱脂肪层中，通过湿滴在空气中传播。在凉爽干燥的条件下传播得最好，这种条件可能有助于保持传染性颗粒的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/mbio.03452-22">完整性</a>并在空中飞沫。<br><br>冠状病毒与流感有足够的相似之处，大多数专家预计它也会在冬季继续传播。这两种病毒都存在于敏感的皮肤中。两者都喜欢通过气溶胶移动。两者都是相对较快的进化者，往往不会产生持久的抗感染免疫力，而这些因素有利于以相当稳定的速度重复攻击人群。出于这些原因，埃默里大学病毒学家 Anice Lowen 预计 SARS-CoV-2 将继续表现出“世界温带地区明显的冬季季节性”。冬季也是我们的身体<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev-virology-012420-022445">更容易受到</a>呼吸道细菌感染的时期：寒冷、干燥的空气会干扰将微生物从鼻子和喉咙中排出的粘液的运动；干旱还会使这些通道内的细胞枯萎和死亡。由于维生素 D 供应不足，某些免疫防御系统可能会变得有些困倦。<br><br>这些都不能阻止 SARS-CoV-2 在炎热的天气中传播，即使专家们不确定该病毒为何如此容易引发夏季浪潮。许多其他微生物也可以控制它：肠道病毒、脊髓灰质炎等等。即使是鼻病毒和腺病毒这两种最常见的感冒原因，也往往会全年传播，有时会在一年中最热的月份中肆虐。 （许多科学家推测这与这些病毒相对坚固的外层有关，但原因无疑比这更复杂。）对新冠病毒夏季浪潮的一个经常吹捧的解释是，该国某些地区的人们躲在室内，以避暑。战胜炎热。但洛文告诉我，这个论点本身“是站不住脚的”。在工业化国家，人们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cpsc.gov/safety-education/safety-guides/home/indoor-air-pollution-introduction-health-professionals">90% 以上的时间都在室内度过</a>。<br><br>也就是说，许多小的影响的积累可以共同创造一个季节性的临界点。夏季<em>是</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://aytm.com/post/vacations-survey">特别受欢迎的旅行季节</a>，经常参加大型聚会。里弗斯说，距离冬季还有好几个月，感染和疫苗接种也很多，每年的这个时候，人群免疫力也可能处于相对较低的水平。此外，尽管 SARS-CoV-2 与流感有很多相似之处，但它本身就是一种野兽：迄今为止，它对人类的影响更长期、更<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/12/covid-common-cold-status-differentiation/672472/">严重</a>，并且以更快的速度产生席卷人群的变种。这些动态都会影响波浪何时出现。<br><br>尽管某些身体防御能力确实会在寒冷中下降，但数据并不支持夏季免疫力单方面更强的观点。纽约“我们行动环境正义”组织的环境健康主任米凯拉·马丁内斯告诉我，情况远比这复杂。多年来，她和其他研究人员一直在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8987173/">收集</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33817568/">证据</a>，表明我们的身体具有明显的季节性免疫特征——一些防御分子在夏季出现峰值，而另一些则在冬季出现峰值。这些转变的后果尚不明显。但其中一些可以帮助解释冠状病毒何时传播。同样的道理，冬季也不是疾病肆虐的时期。瑞典卡罗林斯卡研究所的免疫学家 Xaquin Castro Dopico 发现，北半球的免疫系统<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25965853/">在冬天可能更容易发炎——</a>是的，这可能会使某些疾病发作更加严重，但也可以改善<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19889749/">反应</a>对于某些疫苗接种。<br><br>所有这些解释都可能适用于新冠病毒夏季的波动——或者也许没有一个适用。 “每个人都希望得到一个非常简单的季节性答案，”马丁内斯告诉我。但这种情况可能根本不存在。马丁内斯告诉我，即使是小儿麻痹症这种在美国被消灭之前的严重<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4474890/">夏季</a>疾病，其季节性的原因几十年来也一直是“一个悬而未决的问题”。<br><br>里弗斯希望，冠状病毒的永久模式可能已经开始显现：冬季的鼎盛时期，以及夏季可能出现的较小的驼峰。 “我们已经进入第四年了，我们年复一年地看到同样的事情，”她告诉我。但一些专家担心，讨论 COVID-19 季节性还为时过早。 SARS-CoV-2 对人类来说仍然很新鲜，其模式<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/kids-babies-getting-covid-exposure-vaccines/673368/">可能与最终形式相去甚远</a>。在极端情况下，研究人员在大流行最初几年观察到的模式可能根本无法预示未来，因为它们概括了如此多的变化：最初缺乏免疫力和快速获得免疫力、病毒的进化、病毒的潮起潮落。面具，等等。耶鲁大学传染病建模师布兰登·奥格布努 (Brandon Ogbunu) 表示，在这种相互抵消的影响中，“你会得到一些违反直觉的动态”，而这种动态不一定会持续很长时间。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/kids-babies-getting-covid-exposure-vaccines/673368/">阅读：新冠疫情的下一阶段现已开始</a><br><br><br>由于现在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.healthdata.org/sites/default/files/files/1_briefing_Global_6.pdf">世界上很多地方都</a>受到感染、接种疫苗或两者兼而有之，而且新冠疫情缓解措施几乎完全消失，全球局势现在的变化不再那么大。病毒本身虽然仍然明显以惊人的速度发生变化，但在一年半多的时间里还没有实现 Omicron 级别的进化跳跃。但目前还没有人能够保证其可预测性。疫苗接种的节奏尚未确定；东北大学的斯卡皮诺也不准备否认病毒进化意外的想法。也许夏季浪潮的发生就表明 SARS-CoV-2 仍将是四季皆宜的微生物。或者它们可能是这场大流行病的死亡之声的一部分——系统中尚未平静下来的噪音。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/summer-covid-wave-2023/674863/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/summer-covid-wave-2023/674863/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Misunderstood Reason Millions of Americans Stopped Going to Church]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>驱赶人们出走的决定性问题是……21世纪美国人的生活是如何运作的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/SNLWHQRKMYXKJeLjdVhRTWLZR4Q=/0x312:3000x2000/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_455600083/original.jpg" alt="长椅上放着一本圣经。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>斯宾塞普拉特/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>在内布拉斯加州林肯市的童年教堂里，几乎所有和我一起长大的人都不再是基督徒了。这并不罕见。过去 25 年里，四千万美国人不再去教堂。这大约占总人口的 12%，这是美国历史上教堂出席率最大的集中变化。作为一名基督徒，我敏锐地感受到这种转变。我和我的妻子想知道那些帮助我们维护自己信仰的机构和社区是否仍然会为我们的四个孩子而存在，更不用说有一天我们可能会有孙子孙女。<br><br>这一变化对整个美国来说也是个坏消息：参与宗教团体通常与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2016/10/28/religion-church-attendance-mortality-column/92676964/">更好的健康状况、更长的寿命</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.philanthropyroundtable.org/magazine/less-god-less-giving/">更高的经济慷慨度</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thepublicdiscourse.com/2018/03/20935/">更稳定的家庭</a>相关——所有这些对于一个孤独率上升的国家来说是迫切需要的、精神疾病、酒精和药物依赖。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/christianity-secularization-america-renewal-modernity/672948/">蒂莫西·凯勒：美国基督教即将复兴</a><br><br>奥兰多福音派教会的牧师吉姆·戴维斯 (Jim Davis) 和福音联盟 (Gospel Coalition) 作家迈克尔·格雷厄姆 (Michael Graham) 撰写的一本新书借鉴了政治学家瑞安·伯吉 (Ryan Burge) 和保罗·朱佩 (Paul Djupe) 对 7,000 多名美国人进行的调查，试图解释为什么人们离开教堂——用书中的行话来说是“去教堂”——以及可以采取什么措施让一些人回来。这本书提出了一个有趣的可能性：如果问题不是教会对成员的要求太多，而是他们要求的不够呢？<br><br><i>大洗礼</i>发现，教会中的宗教滥用和更普遍的道德腐败已经驱赶了人们。当然，这是对许多领袖失败的控诉，他们没有解决教会中的虐待问题。但戴维斯和格雷厄姆还发现，离开教会的人中有很大一部分是出于更平庸的原因而这样做的。这本书指出，驱逐大多数离开者的决定性问题是……21世纪美国人的生活是如何运作的。当代美国根本就不是为了促进相互、关怀或共同生活而设立的。相反，它旨在最大限度地提高职业和财务成功所定义的个人成就。这样的制度给各种形式的社区留下了宝贵的时间和精力，而这些社区对一个人自己的职业生活没有贡献，或者随着年龄的增长，对自己孩子的职业前景没有贡献。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/02/religion-workism-making-americans-miserable/583441/">工作主义</a>在美国占主导地位，正因为如此， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2023/05/03/new-surgeon-general-advisory-raises-alarm-about-devastating-impact-epidemic-loneliness-isolation-united-states.html">美国的社区</a>，包括宗教社区，是一个无法相加的数学问题。<br><br>许多在教会环境中遭受虐待的受害者都可以体会到他们失去信仰能力的时刻，他们几乎感觉自己的信仰正在流失。不过，这本书表明，对于大多数曾经是教会成员但后来离开的美国人来说，离开的过程是渐进的，在许多情况下，他们甚至没有意识到这已经发生了。这不像是从悬崖上跳下来，而更像是开车冲下斜坡，最终意识到你再也看不到你出发的地方了。<br><br>考虑一下格雷厄姆和戴维斯在书中用来描述典型福音派教会成员的复合人物之一：一位在郊区大型教堂长大的 30 多岁女性，在大学期间大力投入校园事工，毕业后搬到了找到了一份全职工作，并开始参加当地教堂的一个年轻人团体。在她 20 多岁的时候，她遇到了一个不太热衷于宗教的男人，他们结婚了，在婚姻早期的某个时刻，在他们的第一个或第二个孩子出生后，他们不再去教堂。也许宝宝睡得不好，当周日早上到来时，呆在家里并在宝宝（最终）入睡时抓住任何可以睡觉的时间会更容易。<br><br>在其他情况下，一个人可能正进入职业生涯中期，从事一项需要每周工作 60 或 70 小时的高压力工作。再加上 15 个小时的通勤时间，突然之间，他们一周的清醒时间已经占到了三分之二。因此，当朋友邀请他们参加周日早上的早午餐时，他们可能想去教堂，但他们也想见那个朋友，因为他们已经好几个月没见到他们了。朋友赢了。<br><br>无论哪种情况几周后，周日去教堂的想法都会带来一定的精神负担——你可能<i>想去</i>，但你也害怕不可避免的关于你去过哪里的问题。当你在脑海中排练对话时，“我没去教堂去和朋友一起吃早午餐”或“我太累了，不能来”听起来不像是令人信服的借口。很快，听起来参加比逃课更难，即使你的某些部分仍然想参加。对许多人来说，潜在的挑战是他们的生活就像一根即将断裂的橡皮筋一样被拉伸，而去教堂最终感觉就像是清单上已经太长的一项。<br><br>在这样的背景下，教会可以做什么？理论上，基督教会可以成为这一切的解药。在我们这个时代，还有什么比一个以真诚的爱为标志的社区更需要的呢？根据每个人的能力和需要分享他们所拥有的东西，定期一起吃饭，慷慨地为邻居服务，并过着安静的美德和祈祷的生活？一个健康的教会可以成为严峻的美国经济中的安全网，在需要时向其成员提供物质援助：婴儿出生后的膳食，裁员后的租金。也许更重要的是，它提醒人们，他们的身份不在于他们的工作或他们赚了多少钱；而在于他们的身份。他们是上帝的孩子，受到爱护和保护，具有无限的价值。<br><br>但一个充满活力、赋予生命的教会需要其成员更多而不是更少的时间和精力。它要求人们将彼此置于事业之上，将祈祷和阅读经文置于成就之上。在一个非教会化的时代，这似乎是一个艰难的推销。如果人们已经离开——特别是如果他们离开是因为他们感到太忙、精疲力尽而无法定期去教堂——为什么他们想成为一个对他们要求如此之高的教会的一员呢？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/01/us-religious-affiliation-rates-declining/672729/">阅读：美国宗教尚未消亡</a><br><br>虽然可以理解，但这并不是一个正确的问题。我们面前的问题并不是我们有一个健康、可持续发展的社会，却没有教会的空间。问题在于，许多美国人所采用的生活方式让我们感到孤独、焦虑，并且不确定如何与其他人一起生活。<br><br>美国教会的悲剧在于，他们如此陷入同一个世界，以至于我们现在发现他们无法为这些受苦的人们提供任何在其他地方更容易找到的东西。美国教会常常满足于充当一种模糊的精神非政府组织，一个由独立的个人组成的组织，他们聚集在一起进行宗教服务，以激励他们，提供实际的生活建议，或提供积极的情感体验。很多时候，并不是一个社区能够通过其传教和生活来见证另一种生活方式。<br><br>神学家斯坦利·豪尔（Stanley Hauer） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.christiancentury.org/article/interview/dangers-providing-pastoral-care">很好地抓住了这个问题</a>，他说：“教牧关怀已经变得痴迷于发达工业社会中人们的个人创伤，他们发现自己的生活缺乏意义。”困难在于，我们当前的秩序所造成的许多伤口和疼痛并不是可以控制或消除的。只有通过改变一个人的生活，成为一个属于完全不同类型的社区的完全不同类型的人，才能解决这些问题。<br><br>去年秋天，我在纽约待了几天，期间参观了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bruderhof.com/">一群和平主义基督徒</a>拥有的房屋，他们靠共同的钱包生活——这意味着成员们没有私人财产，而是分享他们的财产和金钱。他们简单的生活和共同的财务使他们的日程安排更加灵活，从而形成了更紧密的直接社区和对邻居更大的慷慨，以及更丰富的祈祷生活和个人对上帝的奉献，所有这些都得到了对教会的坚定承诺的支持。<br><br>诚然，这是一个极端的例子。但这个社区的蓬勃发展并不是因为它找到了减少对其成员提出的要求的方法，而是因为它找到了一种增加成员相互提供的东西的方法。他们的生活方式使他们摆脱了工作主义的束缚。在这个社区中，评判工作的标准不是它所产生的金钱，而是它所服务的人。在相信 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mereorthodoxy.com/dignity-beyond-accomplishment">尊严建立在成就之上的</a>工人主义文化中，简单地收回这种另一种形式的尊严就变成了一种激进的行为。<br><br>在福音书中，耶稣告诉他的第一批门徒抛弃他们旧的生活方式，甚至放弃他们所在的犁或渔网，如果有必要，甚至留下他们的父母。一个对彼此至少没有这么多期望的教会并不是耶稣所说的真正的教会。如果格雷厄姆和戴维斯是对的，那么它也很可能无法在我们今天面临的挑战中幸存下来。<br><br>大规模的去教会可能是教会新时刻的开始，这个时刻不再那么渴望受人尊敬和成功，也不再那么关注个人与美国价值观和假设的一致。我们可以见证美国传统成功衡量标准之外的另一种生活方式。教会可以塑造更好、更真实的社区，让饥饿者得到食物，弱者得到提升，骄傲者被贬低。这些团体可能没有许多美国教会近年来经常追求的金钱、成功和影响力。但如果这些社区看起来不太像那些教堂，它们也可能看起来更像耶稣期望他的追随者创建的那种社区。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-church-communitiy-participation-drop/674843/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-church-communitiy-participation-drop/674843/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Studios Are Risking Everything]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>长期罢工可能会导致电影院停业。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/QPwGjAj5qgmmN-Hh5jMJnG-Ca40=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/studios_strike/original.jpg" alt="空荡荡的电影院和空白屏幕的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>千年图片/图库库存</figcaption></figure>停工首先是为了钱，同时发生的美国演员工会和美国作家工会的罢工也不例外。演员和编剧想要更多，也希望限制人工智能的使用。制片厂表示，考虑到他们在建立流媒体服务时产生的巨额费用，他们分发的内容几乎没有演员和编剧想要的那么多。他们发现自己陷入了僵局，将行业最重要的资产之一：电影院置于危险之中，从而有可能进一步减少总收益。<br><br>好莱坞有这样的历史：首先将不断变化的消费者习惯视为对影院收入的威胁，然后将其视为追求赚取更大利润的工具。电影公司起初对是否将电影授权给电视网络犹豫不决，然后意识到小屏幕是一个尚未开发的市场。好莱坞与 VHS 进行了殊死搏斗——担心非法盗版和客户合法录制电影制片厂授权给电视和有线电视网络的电影——直到它意识到家庭录像租赁和销售是一座金矿。 VHS 的继任者 DVD <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/08/the-death-of-the-dvd-why-sales-dropped-more-than-86percent-in-13-years.html">的年销售额在 2005 年达到顶峰，达到 163 亿美元</a>，几乎<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/?ref_=bo_nb_yld_secondarytab">是国内票房的两倍</a>，之后因流媒体而出现下滑。在某些方面，院线几乎成了家庭录像带销售的亏本产品。<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gF6K2IxC9O8">正如马特·达蒙（Matt Damon）所说</a>，家庭录像带的销售实际上帮助支撑了“我喜欢的电影类型”（成人电影）的整个市场。<br><br>流媒体的诞生——特别是 Netflix 在线组件的兴起——恰逢 DVD 销量的下降，这为 Netflix 的老板们创造了机会。 “一旦它为观众提供了在客厅沙发上在线观看电影和电视节目的新方式……订阅量猛增了 63%，”Dade Hayes 和 Dawn Chmielewski 在他们的书<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/binge-times-inside-hollywood-s-furious-billion-dollar-battle-to-take-down-netflix-dade-hayes/9780062980007?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《Binge Times: Inside Hollywood&#39;s Furious Billion-Dollar》</em></a>中写道。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/binge-times-inside-hollywood-s-furious-billion-dollar-battle-to-take-down-netflix-dade-hayes/9780062980007?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>打倒 Netflix 之战</em></a><em>。</em> “新兴的流媒体服务的发展是以好莱坞为代价的。 [首席执行官里德]黑斯廷斯和公司巧妙地利用了工作室的薪酬结构，当高管实现财务目标时，他们会支付丰厚的奖金。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/writers-strike-hollywood-wga-union-streaming-platforms/674056/">加文·穆勒：好莱坞的卢德分子</a><br><br>其先发优势、从目光短浅的好莱坞高管手中收购的庞大电影库，以及<em>《纸牌屋</em>》、 <em>《女子监狱</em>》和<em>《怪奇物语》</em>等热门原创剧集，帮助 Netflix 成为一家<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/now/netflix-full-2022-earnings-eps-121625446.html">去年在全球创造收入超过 310 亿美元的</a>公司。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/now/netflix-full-2022-earnings-eps-121625446.html">今年</a>，大约是 2019 年（新冠疫情爆发前的最后<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2020/film/box-office/box-office-us-misses-record-disney-dominates-1203453752/">一年）全球所有电影制片厂票房总和的四分之三</a>。这就是该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX">市值</a>达到 1900 亿美元左右的原因。<br><br>电影公司和他们的企业霸主看着 Netflix 的股价和收入，想知道为什么他们也不能印钞票。这就是为什么在大流行开始之前，工作室都在计划自己转向流媒体。疫情爆发后，他们先跳了起来，但很快就发现自己被淹死了。<br><br>正如马修·鲍尔（Matthew Ball）在他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thestreamingbook.com/">对迄今为止的流媒体战争的权威看法</a>中指出的那样，电影公司向流媒体的转型充满了忧虑，结果也好坏参半。以 NBCUniversal 的竞争者 Peacock 为例，该公司暂时有望实现订阅人数和收入双丰收，但仍在大量流失现金。 “康卡斯特最初表示，从 2020 年到 2024 年，Peacock 单年亏损不会超过 $1B，累积亏损将达到 $2B 峰值，并在 2024 年实现盈亏平衡。然而，Peacock 在 2020 年亏损了 $663MM，$1.7B鲍尔<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thestreamingbook.com/chapters/three-years-into-hollywoods-five-year-plan">写道</a>：“2021 年将损失 2.5 亿美元，2022 年将损失 2.5 亿美元。目前累计损失超过 5 亿美元。”除了有关 Netflix 的新闻外，有关流媒体服务的大多数正面头条<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/05/disney-plus-loses-subscribers-streaming-quarter-bob-iger-1235362109/">都可以归结为</a>“好吧，他们本季度的损失比分析师预期的要少一些”。<br><br>对于大多数这些公司来说，问题不在于收入，而在于收入。这是支出。直到最近，人们花在电视节目和电影上的钱比以往任何时候都多。正如美国电影协会在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.motionpictures.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/MPA-2021-THEME-Report-FINAL.pdf">其 2021 年娱乐业状况报告</a>中指出的那样，2021 年通过流媒体、有线和广播制作了 1,826 部原创剧集。从 2019 年到 2021 年，通过流媒体频道发布的电视节目数量大约增加了一倍。<br><br>制片厂看到这一点后表示：“更多的编剧和演员正在获得更多的工作。你还想从我们这里得到什么？”正如编剧扎克·斯坦茨 (Zack Stentz) 在<em>《纽约时报》</em>上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/30/opinion/hollywood-writers-guild-strike.html">指出的</a>那样，“在流媒体驱动的繁荣时期”报告收入的 WGA 会员数量“从 4,500 人猛增至 6,000 多人”。 WGA 报告称，2022 年收取的费用比以往任何时候都多，匿名流媒体内部人士 Entertainment Strategy Guy 表示，这意味着 WGA 编剧的总薪酬<em>可能</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://entertainmentstrategyguy.com/2023/07/20/exclusive-wga-screenwriter-earnings-likely-broke-records-in-2022/">比以往任何时候都多</a>。这就是为什么迪士尼首席执行​​官鲍勃·艾格（Bob Iger） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/bob-iger-writers-actors-strike-disney-ceo-1235669169/">在电视上轻松自在地表示</a>编剧和演员不切实际，认为“他们正在加剧这个行业已经面临的一系列挑战，坦率地说，这是非常具有破坏性的” ”。<br><br>随着电影公司开始将电影从上映日程上取消，这种混乱即将来临。由赞达亚领衔的米高梅新类型“网球三人组电影”影片《<em>挑战者</em>》 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/film/global/challengers-zendaya-skips-venice-film-festival-sag-aftra-strike-1235672841/">原定在今年的威尼斯电影节上开幕</a>；时间被推迟到 2024 年，希望这位演员届时能够走上红地毯。探照灯影业 (Searchlight Pictures) 将于 9 月至 12 月<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/searchlights-poor-things-emma-stone-september-december-1235447551/">推出</a>欧格斯·兰斯莫斯 (Yorgos Lanthimos) 的新片《可怜的事物》( <em>Poor Things)</em> 。伊森·科恩的<em>《Drive-Away Dolls》</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/dune-part-two-drive-away-dolls-actors-strike-box-office-1235448062/">可能会错过秋季音乐节巡演</a>。 A24 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/a24-problemista-actors-strike-wga-strike-1235444874/">还取消了<em>Problemista 的</em>8 月发布日期</a>。华纳兄弟<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2023/07/dune-part-two-may-be-delayed-thanks-to-hollywoods-strikes#:~:text=Dune%3A%20Part%20Two%2C%20director%20Denis,of%20discussions%20told%20the%20outlet.">可能会</a>取消<em>《沙丘：第二部分》</em>的 11 月上映日期。这将使票房相对贫瘠。<br><br>作为一个在 2020 年一整年都在观看电影制片厂的人，反复将电影推迟三个月（或六、九）个月，希望在大流行消退后上映，我很遗憾地说，这开始让人感觉像新冠疫情重演一样可疑。需要明确的是，只要罢工持续下去，推迟上映日期对于工作室来说是完全合乎逻辑的举动：没有明星就意味着没有促销。但我担心，继之前影院长时间缺席电影之后，影院的电影数量如此之少，可能意味着不再有影院了。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">阅读：为什么你应该关注好莱坞作家的罢工</a><br><br>这也许有点夸张，但也只是轻微夸张。在大流行期间停工期间，美国的屏幕数量<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/movie-theater-screen-losses-ticket-prices-1235346523/">减少了 5%</a> ；损害没有更严重的唯一原因是 AMC 在 2021 年不太可能成为一只迷因股票，这帮助该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.polygon.com/movies/2021/1/29/22256360/amc-stock-price-reddit-rally-robinhood-debt-conversion">偿还了 6 亿美元的债务</a>。但<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/ytd/">今年迄今为止，</a>票房收入仍比 2019 年低近 20%，比 2018 年低近 25%。观众对与大流行相关的影院关闭相对理解，并已开始回归，但在事情重回正轨时再次让他们放弃看电影的习惯可能会产生可怕的后果。<br><br>这些后果对于该行业的<em>每个人</em>来说都是可怕的。院线上映仍然是任何一部电影货币化的最佳且最一致的个人方式。它们是电影<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thebulwark.com/moving-films-to-vod-cant-make-up-the-revenue-the-traditional-theatrical-model-generates/">收入瀑布</a>的顶端。尽管某些电影（尤其是中低预算影片）从非院线收入中获得的总收入可能高于院线收入，但在完成盈利能力方面，院线发行仍然是最大的难题。即使是家庭发行方面的成功实验<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/07/business/media/universal-premium-video-on-demand.html">，例如环球影业的高级视频点播窗口</a>（制片厂对仍在影院上映的大片收取额外费用），也依赖于影院放映所带来的声望提升。影院上映是顾客愿意花 20 美元租一部电影的原因。<br><br>所有这些都表明，艾格在一个非常狭隘的意义上是正确的：这对娱乐业来说是一个颠覆性的时期，长时间的关闭可能是灾难性的，导致每个人的钱都减少。但这种因新冠疫情而加速的破坏是工作室自己希望复制 Netflix 模式的直接结果，并将院线上映的承重墙视为装饰性的小玩意，很容易拆除，以完成一些花哨的开放式平面图。是华纳兄弟探索频道首席执行官大卫·扎斯拉夫 (David Zaslav) 钟爱的 HGTV 播出的家居装修节目中的首选。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-actor-guild-strike/674848/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-actor-guild-strike/674848/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[America Is Drowning in Packages]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在亚马逊时代，UPS 工人的工作是不可能完成的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/V6dZ4_O0a4054tchlComWJ1bWms=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/ups_final_2/original.jpg" alt="被包裹包围的地球仪" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>当 UPS 送货工人上次罢工是在 1997 年时，他们的工作性质截然不同。亚马逊当时还只是一家在线书店，距首次销售仅两年时间。购买牛仔裤、新家具或其他任何东西，仍然需要大多数人开车前往当地购物中心。当国际卡车司机兄弟会周二宣布它已与 UPS 达成一项临时协议时，该协议将避免罢工并让数十万工会成员保住工作，这些工人在美国人生活中的角色已经发生了根本性的变化。<br><br>新合同还需要得到工会成员的批准，它来得也不算太早。 UPS 处理的货物数量如此之大，据该公司估计，其员工所处理的货物约占该国国内生产总值的 6%，并且该公司运送的包裹占美国所有包裹的近四分之一。互联网零售和满足其需求的送货服务量使美国更加依赖困难的劳动密集型工作，即所谓的最后一英里包裹递送。该国的基础设施和劳动力仍在努力追赶。<br><br>即使在亚马逊时代，现在在美国递送的包裹数量听起来也是完全荒谬的。 2000 年，美国邮政服务公司（美国最大的包裹托运商）递送了 24 亿个包裹。到 2022 年，这一数字已激增至 72 亿。 UPS 现在每年处理 52 亿个国内包裹，而 2000 年处理的包裹数量为 32 亿个，而亚马逊的物流业务<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-to-launch-delivery-service-that-would-vie-with-fedex-ups-1518175920">直到 2018 年</a>才开始认真运送自己的包裹，现已成为该国第三大托运商，运送了近 50 亿件包裹。但不是几乎所有）该公司去年的包裹。所有这些包裹都将发送给经过零售商培训的客户群，他们预计包裹会在短短几天内到达，这比以前的周转预期要快得多。<br><br>您可能只会注意到每周送到<em>您</em>家的包裹很少（平均家庭有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pitneybowes.com/content/dam/pitneybowes/us/en/shipping-index/22-pbcs-04529-2021-global-parcel-shipping-index-ebook-web-002.pdf">三到四个</a>）。 But every single time you get one, that same day there are more than 50 million other people in the country refreshing their tracking info and checking their doorbell-camera feeds to see if their new shoes or prescription refill has arrived too. And those packages had to be loaded onto a series of trucks, driven to an address, and then carried to a welcome mat by humans.<br><br> Spraying America with a nonstop fire hose of parcels has consequences that are tough for workers and not always visible to the rest of us. More packages require <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucks-roads-damage-traffic-supply-chain-11643210764">more trucks</a> on the road, which means more semis on the country&#39;s interstates and more oversize delivery vehicles on residential streets, worsening traffic for everyone. These vehicles put enormous stress on roads and bridges, requiring more frequent repairs. Streets built primarily for passenger cars can be too narrow or have turns too tight for even the most skilled drivers of cargo vehicles to navigate easily, and conducting so many home deliveries a year inevitably results in accidents, stuck vehicles, and injuries. These same roads tend not to have easy spots for trucks to park when it&#39;s time to actually make a delivery, so they block streets and create more traffic. And each driver has to do it over and over again, dozens of times a day, until the country&#39;s tens of millions of daily packages are delivered and each of hundreds of thousands of cargo vehicles is empty.<br><br> Once a package is off the truck, things aren&#39;t necessarily much easier. Across the country, the median age of local housing stock predates the wide adoption of online shopping, which means that most homes were built before so many of us were getting stuff delivered multiple times a week while away at work. Mailboxes are mostly still the size that they&#39;ve always been, so drivers need to chuck your stuff onto your porch or behind a bush and hope for the best. In apartment complexes, just gaining entry can be a struggle, and many older properties don&#39;t have a mail room big enough to store everything safely. Unless you live in a luxury building, you probably don&#39;t have a front desk with an attendant to accept packages in your stead. And when a bunch of brand-new, unsecured stuff is lying around, some of it is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2019/11/stealing-amazon-packages-age-nextdoor/598156/">bound to get stolen</a> , though assuming theft can be misguided: Package volume is so high and getting them all to the right place is such intricate work that a lot of missing packages were <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/02/nyregion/online-shopping-package-theft.html">simply misdelivered</a> .<br><br> And yet the size of delivery workforces at the country&#39;s major shippers has not increased at the same rate as the boom in packages and the ever-shortening customer expectations on shipping time. Many shipping companies have hired lower-paid part-time workers to fill the gaps instead of creating new full-time jobs, and a significant portion of Amazon&#39;s deliveries are made by gig workers who use their own vehicles and are paid by the package.<br><br> Gig worker or not, all of this work takes place every day of the year and mostly outside, so drivers are handling more parcels and doing more physical labor in a climate that&#39;s becoming more extreme, and they&#39;re doing it largely in cargo vehicles that lack air-conditioning. UPS drivers have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/20/business/ups-postal-workers-heat-stroke-deaths.html">died on the job</a> from heat exposure, and in negotiations between the Teamsters and UPS, air-conditioning for delivery vehicles became a major sticking point. (The union&#39;s new contract, if ratified, would guarantee AC in new delivery vehicles and add better ventilation to old ones.)<br><br> Still, better pay and safety improvements are only the first steps to address the larger spectrum of issues that delivery workers face in moving around so many packages so quickly. Improvements to road and bridge safety are not sexy line items on government budgets, and the trucks will keep rolling whether those improvements are made or not. It may just be impossible to fully retrofit the delivery economy that&#39;s been foisted on Americans by tech companies into the physical reality of daily life. Shippers are going to keep trying anyway.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ups-strike-union-contract-package-deliveries/674864/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ups-strike-union-contract-package-deliveries/674864/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump’s Legal Turmoil Just Keeps Getting Worse]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>更糟糕的是<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ZmVTDGZyYTnV7IDzF1gryy9M3zk=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/trump_1/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>斯科特·摩根/路透社</figcaption></figure><small><em>更新于 2023 年 7 月 28 日东部时间晚上 8:09</em></small><br><br>昨天，特别检察官杰克·史密斯在佛罗里达州联邦法院获得了针对唐纳德·特朗普及其助手沃尔廷·诺塔的机密文件案的替代起诉书。修订后的起诉书增加了一名新被告，海湖庄园的物业经理卡洛斯·德奥利维拉，以及两项新的妨碍司法罪名，罪名是试图“改变、销毁、毁坏或隐藏证据”。新指控源于特朗普、诺塔和德奥利维拉于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/now/video/trump-de-oliveira-and-nauta-allegedly-tried-to-delete-video-footage-at-mar-a-lago-189438533520">2022 年夏天</a>共同试图删除海湖庄园的监控录像的指控。 This all allegedly occurred amid the FBI&#39;s attempts to secure the return of a huge quantity of classified documents that Trump took from the White House—a frustrated effort that culminated in the government&#39;s execution of a search warrant at the property on <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/08/politics/mar-a-lago-search-warrant-fbi-donald-trump/index.html">August 8</a> .<br><br> The superseding indictment also adds a new count under the Espionage Act related to a document marked <span class="smallcaps">top secret</span> and identified as a “presentation concerning military activity in a foreign country,” which Trump is described as waving around to people without security clearances at his Bedminster, New Jersey, club. It also charges de Oliveira with repeatedly lying to the FBI when asked about his knowledge of the boxes stored and moved around at Mar-a-Lago.<br><br> The case is only getting more damning for Trump.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-indictment/674345/">David A. Graham: This indictment is different</a><br><br> Recall that the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://d3i6fh83elv35t.cloudfront.net/static/2023/06/trump-indictment.pdf">original indictment</a> alleged that in May 2022, Nauta removed—at Trump&#39;s direction—64 boxes of documents from “the Storage Room” at Mar-a-Lago. Nauta removed 11 more boxes on June 1, according to the indictment. Several <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-indictment-pictures-photos-documents-boxes-mar-a-lago-bathroom/">photographs</a> depicting stacks of disheveled boxes—one with what looks like a copy machine nearby—were reproduced in the indictment. The new obstruction charges involve the storage room and nearby security cameras, which could have picked up footage of people moving boxes after Trump&#39;s lawyers claimed to the FBI <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-lawyer-christina-bobb-speaks-federal-investigators-mar-lago-case-rcna51459">on June 3</a> , in a certified statement, that Trump had returned everything in his possession.<br><br> The superseding indictment alleges that Trump orchestrated a failed attempt to destroy the surveillance-video footage <i>the day after</i> he learned from his lawyer, on June 22, that they were expecting a grand-jury subpoena for production of “any and all surveillance records, videos, images, photographs and/or CCTV from internal cameras,” including from the “ground floor (basement).” On June 23, Trump called de Oliveira and spoke with him for 24 minutes. The subpoena was issued on June 24. The same day, a staff member texted Nauta, who was at Bedminster, that Trump wanted to see him. In less than two hours, Nauta changed his plans to travel to Illinois, instead heading to Mar-a-Lago. On June 25, Nauta and de Oliveira went to the ground-floor basement, “with a flashlight through the tunnel where the Storage Room was located, and observed and pointed out surveillance cameras.”<br><br> On June 27, after confirming that the club&#39;s IT director, referred to as “Employee 4” in the indictment, was available, de Oliveira walked with that person through the basement tunnel, where they had a conversation meant to “remain between the two of them.” De Oliveira told him that “&#39;the boss&#39; wanted the server deleted.” Employee 4 refused, saying that he would not “have the rights to do that.” De Oliveira responded, “What are we going to do?”<br><br> Later that day, according to the indictment, Nauta and de Oliveira “walked through the bushes on the northern edge of The Mar-a-Lago Club property to meet.” Approximately two hours later, Trump called de Oliveira “and they spoke for approximately three and a half minutes.” Later in the summer, two weeks after the FBI conducted its search (it obtained the surveillance footage in July, and the warrant was issued in early August), Nauta called another Trump employee, saying, “Someone just wants to make sure Carlos is good.” The employee responded that de Oliveira “was loyal” to Trump, who called de Oliveira “the same day” and told him that he&#39;d get him an attorney.<br><br> A few things jump out from this narrative, all of which are bad for Trump. The attempt to erase the video footage occurred in direct response to a grand-jury subpoena for the video footage—not prophylactically, routinely, by mistake, or for some other noncriminal reason. This is a big deal for purposes of proving the crime of obstruction, and Trump&#39;s role and influence in the effort to destroy potentially incriminating evidence of interest to a federal grand jury is unmistakable. The fact pattern also bolsters the government&#39;s case that Trump&#39;s efforts to induce others to hide and tamper with evidence were made “knowingly” and “with intent” under the relevant obstruction statute, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/1512">18 USC § 1512(b)(2)</a> . (The new Espionage Act charge also blows apart Trump&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow-show/maddowblog/classified-docs-case-trump-adds-bravado-claim-evolving-story-rcna91563">claim</a> to the Fox News host Bret Baier that there “was not a document per se” involved in the audio recording of him <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2023/06/26/donald-trump-audio-recording-iran-documents/">discussing</a> what appear to be military war plans with folks lacking security clearances.) Meanwhile, the superseding indictment rests on a stream of corroborating evidence—including, according to the indictment, surveillance-video footage; the testimony of several employees; and a trove of text messages and phone records between the key players, among them Trump himself.<br><br> The Mar-a-Lago case is one of two criminal trials Trump is facing so far—the other was brought by the Manhattan district attorney over alleged financial wrongdoing—with at least <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/trump-legal-issues-two-more-174329060.html">two more</a> possibly impending, including one stemming from Trump&#39;s involvement in the violent attempt to thwart the peaceful transition of presidential power on January 6, 2021, and another out of Fulton County, Georgia, over his recorded effort to sway the Georgia secretary of state to “find” enough votes to swing that state into his electoral column. In all of these cases, prosecutors&#39; task is unique in that the defendant is a former president of the United States and the front-runner for the Republican nomination in 2024—both historical firsts. Criminal juries must be unanimous in Manhattan and in federal court, so Trump&#39;s legal team need only secure a single loyalist who will not convict.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/">David A. Graham: Donald Trump&#39;s &#39;horrifying news&#39;</a><br><br> Which is why it&#39;s significant that the narrative underlying the new obstruction charges is so compelling. The tale is reminiscent of the hero&#39;s journey in mythology and literature that was first articulated by Joseph Campbell in 1949 and that underpins countless Hollywood blockbusters, from <i>The Lord of the Rings</i> to <i>Harry Potter</i> . In this narrative, Employee 4 emerges as the hero who rejected Trump&#39;s villainous urges and then came forward with the truth, at his own peril. Prosecutors and law-enforcement officials involved in the case have already <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aol.com/sports/prosecutors-trump-mar-lago-case-154859205.html">faced</a> substantial threats and harassment, both online and in person. Trump last week <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newsweek.com/donald-trump-deranged-jack-smith-election-interference-1814772">called</a> Jack Smith “deranged.” Let&#39;s hope this story ends well for the good guys.<br><br> <small><em>This article originally stated that a single loyalist would result in an acquittal. In fact, a hung jury would result.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 16:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/donald-trump-indictment-jack-smith/674855/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/donald-trump-indictment-jack-smith/674855/</item><item><title><![CDATA[Barbie Is Everything. Ken Is Everything Else.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Hero. Villain. Incel. Warrior. Leader. Beach. Ken is not the star of the <em>Barbie</em> movie, but he is its tragic, plastic heart. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/foIKWTn7yxm9P-n6uFr3fcC8tII=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/ken_hr/original.jpg" alt="瑞恩·高斯林在《芭比娃娃》中饰演肯" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Jaap Buitendijk / Warner Bros. Pictures</figcaption></figure> <small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br> <strong><em>This article contains spoilers for the film</em></strong> <strong>Barbie.</strong><br><br> Earlier this week, Elon Musk announced that he would be rebranding his social-media platform: Twitter is now, simply, X. Speculation abounded as to why Musk would trade a well-known brand for a letter typically associated with rejection and porn: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-rebrand-paypall-x-sounded-like-porn-site-twitter-2023-7">spite</a> , maybe. Or maybe—the most absurd theory, and therefore the most likely—the man who had named his car models “S,” “3,” “X,” and “Y” was doing it, once again, for the lols. Soon after Twitter became X, employees <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/24/technology/twitter-x-elon-musk.html">reported</a> , the conference rooms of its headquarters were rechristened. The staffers Musk hasn&#39;t yet fired can now plan the future of democratized conversation from a meeting room named “s3Xy.”<br><br> X was released, as it happened, the same weekend that the <em>Barbie</em> movie was. The coincidence was eloquent. <em>Barbie</em> is a film about its namesake, definitely, and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">an exploration of impossible womanhood</a> . But it is also a film about Ken—a Ken who, in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">director Greta Gerwig&#39;s rendering</a> , sheds his status as Barbie&#39;s bland accessory to become … a power-addled man-child determined to turn the world into his plaything. No element of <em>Barbie</em> ’s aggressive marketing campaign could have bought the relevance created by a 52-year-old tech titan who, when he is not moving fast and/or breaking things, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musks-humor-jokes-over-years-titter-420-69-2023-4">amuses himself</a> by finding new ways to write “69” into the public record.<br><br> Americans live under gerontocracy, many pundits have argued: Too many of our leaders, having tasted power and then spent decades consolidating it, refuse to cede their spoils to anybody else. The broader truth is even more lamentable, though, because it involves leaders who, unable to contend with power&#39;s responsibilities, treat our future as their toy. Musk and Mark Zuckerberg have spent weeks fueling <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/01/technology/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-match.html">speculation</a> that they will settle their business differences by way of a televised cage match. Americans gave our nuclear codes to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/10/infantilization-of-a-president/542613/">a Brioni-swaddled toddler</a> . We may well <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-2024-election-republican-primary-nomination-opponents/673882/">do it again</a> . We live in the thrall of impetuous boy-kings. No fictional figure has captured the absurdity of that situation, and the tragedy of it, better than a doll who looks like a man but inflicts himself on the world with a boy&#39;s impish glee. Ken demands attention. He throws tantrums. He sows chaos. He threatens the whole order of things. He is the plastic core of <em>Barbie</em> ’s world—and a bleached-blond satire of ours.<br><br> Barbie Land is, allegedly, a place of childish dreams, safe and happy and sterile and pink. “Girl power,” in the land of the dolls, is not a well-lit lie; it is, on the contrary, the only truth that exists—the scaffolding that supports every wall-less Dream House. It shapes not only the Barbies&#39; professional lives (President Barbie, Physicist Barbie, Doctor Barbie) but also their sense of the world they occupy. The Barbies are self-confident and self-actualized and just generally delighted, and of course they are: They have never had reason to be otherwise. In Barbie Land, the Barbies are fond of reminding themselves that every day is “the best day ever.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">Read: What&#39;s the matter with Barbie?</a><br><br> There are Kens in Barbie Land, but they are, like the doll himself, variously decorative and superfluous. Where do the Kens live? What Dream Cars do they drive? Such questions are moot. In a place that treats possessions as proxies for personal fulfillment, the Kens seem to have none. Nor, in a society that equates profession with identity, do they have apparent careers. The Kens do have a job, though: to serve as reliable extras in the Barbies&#39; shiny show. The Kens are there when they&#39;re needed. They&#39;re cheerful. They&#39;re patient. They&#39;re always ready to don sequins and smiles for an intricately choreographed dance number. They are, like pretty much everything else in Barbie Land, aggressively uncomplicated. They are also, as a result, extremely boring.<br><br> Except, that is, for one of them: the Ken who is paired, per the two-by-two logic of Barbie Land, with Stereotypical Barbie. This Ken, played—inhabited—by Ryan Gosling, chafes against his class status. Barbie Land may look like a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://collider.com/themyscira-wonder-woman-series-paradise-lost/">Paradise Island</a> –style matriarchy whose Amazons are 11 inches tall and molded of polyvinyl chloride; Ken, though, is a reminder of the brute limits of its utopia. The film&#39;s most obvious problem comes early on, when Stereotypical Barbie (Margot Robbie) finds herself afflicted by the assorted insults of the human condition (imperfectly browned toast, thoughts of death, cellulite). But Barbie Land&#39;s prefab perfections were imperfect well before Barbie&#39;s crisis. Ken bears the brunt of its errors. He is not merely Barbie&#39;s plaything; he is also the recipient of her casual cruelty. “You can go now,” Barbie tells him, flashing a smile as his face falls. Later: “I don&#39;t want you here.”<br><br> These are the types of lines that have earned <em>Barbie</em> , in the days since its release, some <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/24/if-i-made-a-movie-that-treated-women-the-way-barbie-treats-men-feminists-would-want-me-executed/">indignant</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tmz.com/2023/07/22/barbie-attacked-right-wingers-anti-man-feminist-trash/">accusations</a> of man-hating and sexism and “toxic femininity.” What the criticisms miss, though—or perhaps ignore—is that irony might be present even in a film about toys. The dynamics of Barbie Land are both complicated and simple: Barbie, insulated in its confines, represents—in real-world terms—the beneficiaries of patriarchy. Ken represents, essentially, everybody else. Barbie, in her dismissals of Ken, doesn&#39;t mean to be mean; she treats him thoughtlessly because she has simply never considered that words—or anything, really—might cause hurt. She has never needed to. Comfort, in her society as in ours, is a luxury. The slogans of the human world—and the bleak dynamics that have transformed kindness and empathy from kindergarten lessons into political pleas—make no sense to those who cannot imagine other people&#39;s pain.<br><br> They make a lot of sense to Ken, though. He is, at the outset of the film, the most messily human feature of this plastic world, a tangle of need and hope and, eventually, rage. In the land of hard-set smiles, he winces. Surrounded by endless cheer, he aches. He senses that something is very much amiss. But sensing is all he can do. Barbie Land may have a president and a constitution and a supreme court, but it is, in practice, aggressively apolitical. (Politics is a response to humans and conflicts; Barbie Land allows neither.) And so, having no language or outlet for his frustrations—beleaguered, you might say, by a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/the-feminine-mystique-anniversary-betty-friedan/8751751?ean=9780393934656&amp;ref=&amp;source=IndieBound&amp;title=The+Feminine+Mystique%3A+A+Norton+Critical+Edition+%28Norton+Critical+Editions%29">problem that has no name</a> —Ken simply feels his way through his plight. His want leaves him afflicted with something else that is foreign in Barbie Land: vulnerability.<br><br> Much of <em>Barbie</em> ’s magic comes down to Robbie and Gosling and their ability, as actors, to blend the plastic and the human, the earnest and the camp. Robbie&#39;s performance, for its part, is a matter of distillation. It captures many of the elements that have made the Barbie doll both <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">an enduring icon and an endless controversy</a> —among them her unattainable beauty, her blithe naivete, her whiteness, her thinness, her reminder that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-and-the-myth-of-the-underage-woman/596140/">even children are stalked by the shifting demands of womanhood</a> . Gosling finds similar nuance, but from the opposite direction: Ken is, infamously, a plus-one who is defined by his absence. Gosling fills in the blanks. And he does so by weaving one of the dolls&#39; elemental ironies—Barbie and Ken are teenagers who are routinely mistaken for adults—into his performance.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-and-the-myth-of-the-underage-woman/596140/">Read: The myth of the &#39;underage woman&#39;</a><br><br> Ken, in Gosling&#39;s rendering, lives in a stew of emotions that are always just beyond his control. He is by turns petulant and teeming with possibility, impulsive and self-conscious. Which is also to say that this chisel-jawed doll is, in many ways, a very typical adolescent. Barbie, newly beset by human-borne feeling, shocks herself by crying—first a single tear, and then a flood of them. Gosling&#39;s Ken cries too. But his discord has a stereotypically masculine edge. He erupts into anger. He feels entitled to sex, despite and because of his ignorance of it. He cares, deeply, what the other guys think of him. “You can&#39;t make me look uncool in front of Ken!” he wails at Barbie, panic flashing in his eyes.<br><br> Ken, in the film&#39;s early scenes, takes his tumult out on Barbie. There he is, radiating look-at-me longing. There he is, like Romeo with his poems or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1GoH3M9Kb4g">Lloyd Dobler with his boom box</a> , turning love into a show. He orients his life around Barbie so thoroughly that, before long, he is becoming the one thing a Ken must not be in Barbie Land: a hindrance.<br><br> Ken resents his neediness as much as Barbie does. But Barbie Land offers him no other option. <em>She is everything; he&#39;s just Ken</em> . That is the way of this world. Gosling&#39;s performance channels all of that. And then, powerfully, it escalates the matter: Ken&#39;s need for Barbie becomes so consuming that it curdles into violence. Soon, his hopeful smiles are twisting into sneers. The stubbornness of his desire for Barbie—and his inability to accept her disinterest—begins to evoke the grim entitlements of the incel. His plight becomes everyone else&#39;s threat.<br><br> It&#39;s unsettling, the doll made dangerous. That&#39;s what makes it so effective. The bulk of the film finds Barbie and Ken on a journey that mimics adolescence: Having left the land of protection and play and easy dreams, they are plunged into the realities of the human world—and the hard transactions of adulthood. The dolls must navigate a place that has no shortage of language for its political condition: <em>patriarchy</em> , <em>marginalization</em> , <em>objectification</em> , <em>oppression</em> .<br><br> Ken loves it. Walking on a street in LA—clothed, through an accident of circumstance in the plot and inspired costuming choices beyond it, in fringe-covered Western wear—he begins to strut. He feels, for the first time, respected, admired, seen. Barbie, meanwhile, is the one made to feel—and then to fear—the vulnerabilities of her gender. One of <em>Barbie</em> ’s best jokes finds Ken, having returned to Barbie Land, playing her a song on his guitar—singing not <em>to</em> Barbie, he makes clear, but <em>at</em> her. Ken croons and crows, entranced by the romance of his gesture, holding Barbie&#39;s gaze and refusing to let it go. The absurdity of it all is punctured by the lyrics of the song he chooses—one that became, in the real world, a hit: <em>I wanna push you around, well I will, well I will / I wanna push you down, well I will, well I will</em> …<br><br> Adolescence is a time of extremes. And Ken, having experienced manhood in a man&#39;s world, reacts to his new situation with juvenile glee. Soaking up his surroundings as a child might—alive, always, to the images and messages around him—he intuits first that manliness is everything in the real world, and second, that manliness must involve horses. (Patriarchy, he concludes, is the system “where men on horses run everything.”) He is entranced by images of Rocky Balboa and Bill Clinton, captivated by the guys who high-five one another at the gym. Back in Barbie Land, importing the lessons he&#39;s learned from reality, he takes over Barbie&#39;s Dream House. His Mojo Dojo Casa House is a bachelor pad and a bar and, in its overall aesthetic, a tribute to John Wayne&#39;s influence on American tropes of masculinity. Its decor features, obviously, an abundance of horses.<br><br> Ken&#39;s excesses are funny, and foolish, and, except for the house-stealing stuff, pretty relatable. Like any teenager, Ken is figuring out who he is, and trying the world&#39;s possibilities on for size. But his immaturity is not contained, and this is its problem. His adolescent approach to the world, instead, inflicts itself on everyone else. Soon—a plot twist that, for anyone who has followed US politics in recent years, doubles as a twist of the knife—Ken is trying to rewrite Barbie Land&#39;s constitution.<br><br> There&#39;s an ominous kind of justice to Ken&#39;s attempts to inject himself into the political life of Barbie Land. It is a zero-sum solution to the problems of a zero-sum world. The Ken doll has been called, over the years, a “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/22/style/ken-barbie-doll-biography-cec/index.html">drip with seriously abridged genitalia</a> ,” “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a44285254/the-history-of-ken-barbie/">an uncomfortably freighted icon of anti-masculinity</a> ,” and—by Gosling, during <em>Barbie</em> ’s promotional tour—“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/22/entertainment/ryan-gosling-ken-barbie-doll-cec/index.html">an accessory, and not even one of the cool ones</a> .” When Ken was featured in 2010&#39;s <em>Toy Story 3</em> , he found himself on the receiving end of the following line: “You ascot-wearing pink-noser! You&#39;re not a toy … You&#39;re a purse with legs!”<br><br> The insult was made all the more insulting because it was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A-H9-CLfOWg">delivered</a> by a tuber with detachable limbs and anger-management issues. But Mr. Potato Head was simply saying what everyone already knew: The defining fact of Ken is that Ken is defined by Barbie. That alone makes it hard not to feel bad for the guy. And for many of <em>Barbie</em> ’s viewers, his plight may feel extremely familiar. A key moment in the film, as my colleague Shirley Li <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">wrote</a> , comes from one of its human protagonists, Gloria (America Ferrera), who summons a life&#39;s worth of frustration into a speech about the challenges—and the utter irrationality—of being a woman in a world shaped by men. Another key moment, though, comes from Ken. It&#39;s near the end of the movie, and he&#39;s finally getting the one thing he&#39;s really wanted: Barbie is listening to him. He&#39;s telling her what it&#39;s like to be dimmed so that somebody else might shine. And then he adds the kicker: “It doesn&#39;t feel good, does it?”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">Read: The surprising key to understanding the</a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/"><em>Barbie</em></a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">film</a><br><br> The critics who have accused <em>Barbie</em> of misandry might want to watch that moment, if indeed they ever watched it at all, once more. Ken&#39;s line gives punctuation, effectively, to Gloria&#39;s speech. And it does what our current political slogans beg us, fruitlessly, to do: It empathizes. Ken doesn&#39;t really want political power, he discovers; it&#39;s a lot of work. (Plus, disappointingly, horses are merely “men-extenders.”) What he really seeks is the power to figure out who he is on his own terms. Does Ken want Barbie at all? Would he, as the film hints, rather be paired with another Ken? What would he choose to be were his identity broader than Barbie and Beach?<br><br> Ken is, by the end of the film, not merely a doll who has known life in the human world; he is also a guy who understands what it&#39;s like to be treated as an extra in someone else&#39;s story. In him, the debates that shape—and limit—our political possibilities become elegantly straightforward. Ken is a person who is denied the full dignity of his personhood. That—whatever your worldview, whatever your particular circumstance, whatever your feelings about the word <em>patriarchy</em> —is a blatant form of injustice.<br><br> But Ken is also, at the story&#39;s conclusion, a guy who has escaped from his arrested development. He has come to embody one of <em>Barbie</em> ’s core ideas: that patriarchy is a profound form of immaturity. It causes childishness. It results from it too. Here is one reason for hope, though, as our very real men-children keep trying to remake the world into their Mojo Dojo Casa House: For Ken, immaturity becomes what it is for most people—a phase on the way to something better. Ken doesn&#39;t become human. He does, however, grow up.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 13:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Song That First Captured Sinéad O’Connor’s Power]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Before “Nothing Compares 2 U” made her a household name, a single from the Irish singer&#39;s first album established her as a creative force. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/lmLTodOiq2ye6mR1qmm64rNRRFk=/0x402:3735x2503/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_168935759/original.jpg" alt="The singer Sinéad O’Connor, performing in concert" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Frans Schellekens / Redferns / Getty</figcaption></figure> There&#39;s a candid moment in <em>Nothing Compares</em> , the 2022 documentary by Kathryn Ferguson about the life and career of Sinéad O&#39;Connor, when the singer says, “It was such a shock for me to become a pop star. It&#39;s not what I wanted. I just wanted to scream.” O&#39;Connor, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/26/arts/music/sinead-oconnor-dead.html">who died yesterday</a> at the age of 56, became famous in the late &#39;80s, when she was barely out of her teens. In 1990, her cover of Prince&#39;s “Nothing Compares 2 U” became not only her signature song, but also a chart-topper in numerous countries—a sweep that thrust a shy Irish kid under the hot sun of international scrutiny.<br><br> Rather than moderate her voice, she kept screaming. And over the years, her many controversial protests and statements tended to overshadow her breathtaking body of work. When people vow to murder you (as they did after she ripped up a photo of Pope John Paul II on <em>Saturday Night Live</em> ) and Frank Sinatra publicly threatens to assault you (as he did when she refused to have the American national anthem played at a New Jersey concert in 1990), it&#39;s hard to direct attention back to the thing that actually made you famous: your music.<br><br> The fact that she became a pop star—and not just any pop star, but one of the most distinct, most outspoken, and most influential of all time—may have been a surprise to her. But it couldn&#39;t have been a surprise to her fans. Few things made that clearer than her first hit, “Mandinka.” The song, which became a Top 20 hit in the United Kingdom, was the standout single and obvious earworm from her superb 1987 debut LP, <em>The Lion and the Cobra</em> . It was an ambitious album, collecting dark accounts of childhood trauma (“Troy”) and layered explorations of lust and consent (“I Want Your (Hands on Me)”). Amid these deeper, more demanding singles, <em>The Lion and the Cobra</em> needed an upbeat invitation. “Mandinka” was it. <br><br><div class="oembed" data-oembed-name="www.youtube.com" data-oembed-src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h08pCvyKfbs"><figure class="c-embedded-video"><div class="embed-wrapper" style="display: block; position:relative; width:100%; height:0; overflow:hidden; padding-bottom:75.00%;"><iframe allow="autoplay; fullscreen; encrypted-media; picture-in-picture;" allowfullscreen="true" class="embedly-embed lazyload" data-src="//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/media.html?src=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2Fh08pCvyKfbs%3Ffeature%3Doembed&amp;display_name=YouTube&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3Dh08pCvyKfbs&amp;image=https%3A%2F%2Fi.ytimg.com%2Fvi%2Fh08pCvyKfbs%2Fhqdefault.jpg&amp;key=8164a61223cb4585ad276041728caca9&amp;type=text%2Fhtml&amp;schema=youtube" frameborder="0" height="480" scrolling="no" style="position:absolute; width:100%; height:100%; top:0; left:0; border:0;" title="YouTube 嵌入" width="640" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></figure></div> Written when O&#39;Connor was still a teenager struggling to make her way as an aspiring expat in London, “Mandinka” is a propulsive anthem that straddles pop and the loosely knit genre of alternative rock, which wouldn&#39;t see its full commercial triumph until the &#39;90s. The lyrics don&#39;t convey a narrative as such, but like so many of O&#39;Connor&#39;s songs, “Mandinka” synthesizes and projects a string of images, recriminations, and mantras. What coalesces in her words is a barrage of beefs with the patriarchy that refuses to sacrifice poetry for purpose. The title comes from Alex Haley&#39;s <em>Roots</em> , which mentions the Gambian ethnic group of Mandinka. “Mandinka” was slightly ahead of its time, but it&#39;s also very much in the same camp as contemporaneous songs such as Neneh Cherry&#39;s “Buffalo Stance” and Enya&#39;s “Orinoco Flow.” (Unsurprisingly, her fellow Irish artist Enya made a guest appearance on <em>The Lion and the Cobra</em> .)<br><br> “Mandinka,” at its core, is a song of defiance. O&#39;Connor threw every bit of texture and range—snarling, chanting, cooing, and, yes, screaming—she could into the song, and the result was a smack in the face of conventionality. Hurt is part of the DNA of “Mandinka,” even as O&#39;Connor exults in her power to withstand it: “I don&#39;t know no shame / I feel no pain / I can&#39;t see the flame,” she sings with venom. Again, defiance. But it&#39;s not a denial or some bluff—instead, it&#39;s an acknowledgement of how she&#39;s proudly used her scar tissue as raw material.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/04/how-nothing-compares-2-u-endured/391122/">Read: How “Nothing Compares 2 U” endured</a><br><br> “Soon I can give you my heart,” O&#39;Connor chants at the end of “Mandinka.” That&#39;s exactly what she did: The lushly romantic “Nothing Compares 2 U” came out three years later, becoming the song that most people immediately think of when they hear O&#39;Connor&#39;s name. But the power of “Nothing Compares 2 U” partly stemmed from the fact that O&#39;Connor had already proved herself capable of far greater force on <em>The Lion and the Cobra</em> , and in “Mandinka” in particular. Her first appearance on US television was on <em>Late Night With David Letterman</em> , and her performance of the single is telling. She wears a spiked denim jacket like punk-rock armor, holding her arms in front of her and twisting back and forth like she&#39;s dodging blows in a boxing ring.<br><br> Perhaps the most succinct tribute to the impact of “Mandinka” is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rB3qDlu5Nvg">a video of Fiona Apple</a> , posted to YouTube in 2017. In it, Apple lies in bed with her laptop while singing and air-punching along to O&#39;Connor&#39;s 1989 Grammy performance. It was a historic one: Nominated that year for Best Female Rock Vocal, O&#39;Connor infamously drew Public Enemy&#39;s bull&#39;s-eye logo on her head to protest the fact that the newly minted Grammy for Best Rap Performance was awarded off camera. (On Twitter yesterday, the group&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/MrChuckD/status/1684278409868763160">Chuck D</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/FlavorFlav/status/1684305143574003715">Flavor Flav</a> both remembered the protest.)<br><br> When the chorus hits, Apple ups the volume and kisses the screen. It&#39;s a gesture of joyous release and empowerment that mirrors the song itself. “I didn&#39;t mean to be strong,” O&#39;Connor says at the start of Ferguson&#39;s documentary. “I wasn&#39;t thinking to myself, <em>I must be strong</em> . I didn&#39;t know I was strong.” All it takes is one listen to “Mandinka,” though, for anyone else to know, feel, and find themselves strengthened by her strength.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 18:02:19 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[American Family Life Should Not Be This Volatile]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Welcome to the age of tremors. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/svoxez6gbJG4KFeL--3BSnqxm9s=/0x0:3333x4166/648x810/media/img/2023/07/27/MG179418_copy/original.jpg" alt="The silhouette of a man leaning over his child" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Gueorgui Pinkhassov / Magnum</figcaption></figure> <span class="smallcaps">Parenthood has always involved unpredictability</span> : wake-ups at 2 am, calls from school, the dreaded words <em>my stomach hurts</em> . This daily variance frequently stems from a sick or scared child, and is part of the basic dynamic of family life. Yet today&#39;s parents in the US also face rising external disruptions and a degradation of the institutions that are meant to provide stability. The result is that many families are regularly knocked off their feet by problems that are more than inconvenient but less than catastrophic. This breeds parental stress, insecurity, and exhaustion. Americans have entered, in short, an age of tremors.<br><br> The nation has been on this course for the past half century. Starting in the 1970s, a series of economic- and social-policy decisions led to what the political scientist Jacob Hacker has termed the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-risk-shift-the-new-economic-insecurity-and-the-decline-of-the-american-dream-jacob-s-hacker/9780190844141?affiliate_id=atl-347">“great risk shift”</a> from government and corporations onto households. Hacker&#39;s idea mainly refers to economic changes, such as the private sector&#39;s shift from guaranteed pensions to stock-market-dependent 401(k)s. But this notion of a “DIY society” can extend to the numerous ways parents—especially mothers—are asked to “hold it all together,” the University of Wisconsin at Madison sociologist Jessica Calarco told me. For example, the rise of double-earner households was not met with policies like affordable child care or mandatory paid leave. Instead, families have been forced to navigate confusing and competitive marketplaces to acquire basic services such as day care and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/01/summer-day-camps-activities-childcare/672837/">summer camp</a> , and they are largely on their own to deal with any breakdowns.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/06/us-paid-parental-leave-child-welfare-tax-credit/661276/">Read: The US leaves parents on their own for a reason</a><br><br> What&#39;s new in the 2020s is that these breakdowns are occurring more frequently. Consider the series of challenges families have faced in recent years. There has been a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/17/health/formula-shortage-one-year-later/index.html">terrible shortage of infant formula</a> , as well as children&#39;s medicines such as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/01/05/why-childrens-tylenol-shortage">Tylenol</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aap.org/en/pages/amoxicillin-shortage-antibiotic-options-for-common-pediatric-conditions/">amoxicillin</a> , and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/students-struggle-academically-fight-in-schools-amid-adderall-shortage-209d01e0">Adderall</a> . Child care has become even <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/07/us-childcare-programs-expensive-underfunded/670927/">scarcer and more expensive</a> —and, because of staffing shortages, programs regularly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kcrg.com/2023/07/25/families-hunt-new-child-care-after-iowa-city-facility-suddenly-closes/">close</a> or reduce hours <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://vtdigger.org/2022/08/02/closure-of-a-child-care-center-in-essex-junction-sends-families-scrambling-for-options/">with little notice</a> . Extreme heat has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/01/us/michgan-schools-heat.html">forced school closures</a> ; wildfire smoke from Canada has caused some US <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/07/23/summer-camp-canada-wildfire-smoke/">summer camps</a> to delay their start times.<br><br> Some of this volatility is because of climate change, public-policy decisions, or corporate-profit maximizing. Some of it is the result of multiple factors. The infant-formula crisis was caused mainly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/doj-investigating-abbott-plant-at-the-center-of-2022-baby-formula-shortage#:~:text=The%20factory's%20closure%20in%20February,banks%2C%20friends%20and%20doctor's%20offices.">by a single factory shutting down, a predicament foreshadowed by</a> policy makers enabling a handful of companies to control <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/economy/the-current-baby-formula-shortage-sheds-light-on-longstanding-weaknesses-within-the-industry">nearly the entire market</a> . Additionally, as the labor economist Aaron Sojourner told me, there has been a significant rise of “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.demos.org/sites/default/files/publications/Scheduling_Hourly_Workers_Demos.pdf">just-in-time scheduling</a> ”—a model where businesses operate with the barest minimum of employees who can be called in or sent home on very short notice—in low-wage industries including retail, food service, and call centers. This leads to instability in the lives of workers, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rsfjournal.org/content/8/5/24.abstract">especially parents</a> , and increases the risk of something going awry for customers if a sole employee quits or cannot make their shift. Yet <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hrdive.com/news/a-running-list-of-states-and-localities-with-predictive-scheduling-mandates/540835/">only one state and a few cities</a> have laws limiting just-in-time scheduling.<br><br> At the same time, decades of neglect are causing public systems to break down. A lack of adequate funding and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/recoding-america-why-government-is-failing-in-the-digital-age-and-how-we-can-do-better-jennifer-pahlka/9781250266774?affiliate_id=atl-347">modernized processes</a> has led to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.baltimorebrew.com/2023/07/18/three-public-pools-have-yet-to-open-in-baltimore-hanging-residents-out-to-dry/">decaying public services</a> and hollowed-out government offices with poor responsiveness. Applications for child-care assistance <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kcur.org/politics-elections-and-government/2023-05-10/missouri-families-cant-get-help-affording-child-care-because-of-bureaucratic-hurdles">can be a nightmare to complete</a> , and even well-resourced states like New York and Illinois have recently had major problems getting <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wgntv.com/news/illinois/some-childcare-providers-forced-to-close-after-not-getting-paychecks-from-state/">timely payments to child-care providers</a> . Parents of children with disabilities are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnet.com/personal-finance/social-security-disability-claims-wait-record-high-how-to-avoid-delays/">facing down</a> record-long application-processing times and extremely limited support staff.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">The age of tremors helps explain</span> a seemingly odd disconnect between people&#39;s perceptions of their personal lives and of the way the country is going. <em>The Atlantic</em> ’s Derek Thompson <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2022/06/american-economy-negative-perception-inflation/661149/">described this phenomenon</a> as “Everything is terrible, but I&#39;m fine,” pointing to the tension between contemporary indicators such as healthy disposable income and a sense of economic gloom. For many parents, I might extend the description to “Everything is terrible; I&#39;m holding on, but what&#39;s going to go wrong next?”<br><br> Psychologists are clear that a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://psychcentral.com/stress/stress-and-the-concept-of-control">reasonable sense of control</a> is a key component of mental health. Having to worry about Canadian wind directions or scouring a half dozen stores for medicine to bring down your child&#39;s fever are not only practical pain points; they foster a general atmosphere of instability. Some parents of young children <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/17/health/formula-shortage-one-year-later/index.html">still reported lingering fear and anxiety</a> about formula supply after shelves were filled again.<br><br> Such constant precarity takes an emotional toll regardless of one&#39;s bank account. Research shows <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapediatrics/fullarticle/2789946">significant declines in parents&#39; mental health</a> since before the pandemic, and recent years have brought <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/05/well/family/parental-burnout-symptoms.html">high levels of parental exhaustion and burnout</a> , as well as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsroom.thecignagroup.com/loneliness-epidemic-persists-post-pandemic-look">loneliness</a> . About three-quarters of parents are very or somewhat concerned that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.capita.org/thinkofthechildren">climate change will harm their children</a> or other young children they know. This stress and insecurity can easily <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Tumbleweed-Society-Working-Caring-Insecurity/dp/0199957711?asin=0199957711&amp;revisionId=&amp;format=4&amp;depth=1">trickle down</a> to the whole family.<br><br> A simple rejoinder is that none of this is new. Parents a century ago could not count on antibiotics because they were not commercially available. But consider the more recent past: Today&#39;s parents have less predictability than those in the last quarter of the 20th century. As the Stanford sociologist Marianne Cooper wrote in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/cut-adrift-families-in-insecure-times-marianne-cooper/9780520277670?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>Cut Adrift: Families in Insecure Times</em></a> , the trends that began at the time of the great risk shift brought about substantial increases in income and job instability by the 2000s.<br><br> Moreover, until the past few decades, social institutions and bonds have been better prepared to stand in the gap. Labor unions, fraternal associations, and especially <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/28/opinion/religion-affiliation-community.html">faith communities</a> provide not merely a sense of connectivity but also material support such as meals after a birth or trusted people who can watch the kids in a pinch. These networks have been experiencing a steady decline in membership.<br><br> A permanent age of tremors is not, however, inevitable. Policy makers can both stabilize the ground and help families deal with the quakes. The first step is making healthy, predictable family life a policy priority. Laws that strengthen the child-care system, provide robust paid leave, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fortune.com/2023/04/17/irs-phone-wait-times-taxes/">reinvest in public services</a> and lower <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2021/07/how-government-learned-waste-your-time-tax/619568/">their administrative burdens</a> , and restrict just-in-time scheduling are all ways to shift risks from families back onto government and corporations. As a guiding principle, policy makers should reduce chaos, liberating parents and children to deepen their connections to one another and their community.<br><br> Perhaps the saddest thing about the status quo is that this should be an age of wonders for families. We live in an era when modern medicine has eliminated many childhood diseases and is regularly developing new <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/fda-approves-rsv-injection-infants-rcna94698">treatments</a> . There has been a resurgence of interest in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/07/raising-kid-american-city/661506/">developing child-friendly communities</a> that can withstand climate disruption by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tpl.org/parks-address-climate-change-report">expanding and upgrading parks</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/2023/06/30/future-of-the-playground/">creating more natural playgrounds</a> . Technological tools make connecting with loved ones in far-flung parts of the country easier than ever. Parents could have so much to enjoy and look forward to—if they weren&#39;t constantly bracing for the next shake.<br><br> <small><em>​​When you buy a book using a link on this page, we receive a commission. Thank you for supporting</em> The Atlantic <em>.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:15:02 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/</item></channel></rss>